    <meta name="description" content="Debates about the future of the monarchy come in waves. Reforming the 300-year-old Act of Succession, which bars all but Protestants from the throne, is the latest focus of attention. A motion before the House of Commons in the name of the Scottish Nationalists calls for its repeal. As both the heir to the throne and his elder son are members of the Church of England, the matter is not really very pressing, but that is the nature of the question; it is always difficult to know where to start."/>
        <title>
			Debate the monarchy's future (but nothing will change) -
				Andreas Whittam Smith, Commentators - The Independent</title>
<meta name="proximic_title" content="Debate the monarchy's future (but nothing will change)"/>
    <meta name="icx_authors" content=""/>
    <meta name="icx_byline" content=""/>
    <meta name="icx_copyright" content="2000 Independent News Media"/>
    <meta name="icx_deckheader" content="Debates about the future of the monarchy come in waves. Reforming the 300-year-old Act of Succession, which bars all but Protestants from the throne, is the latest focus of attention. A motion before the House of Commons in the name of the Scottish Nationalists calls for its repeal. As both the heir to the throne and his elder son are members of the Church of England, the matter is not really very pressing, but that is the nature of the question; it is always difficult to know where to start."/>
