	<script src="https://web.archive.org/web/20100709181216js_/http://www.independent.co.uk/independent.co.uk/editorial/web/adsense/show_ads.js"></script>

<!-- adSurroundClose -->
<p>

	<div class="body">
		<!-- Check if it is the money section -->
        <p>
			<p>Debates about the future of the monarchy come in waves. Reforming the 300-year-old Act of Succession, which bars all but Protestants from the throne, is the latest focus of attention. A motion before the House of Commons in the name of the Scottish Nationalists calls for its repeal. As both the heir to the throne and his elder son are members of the Church of England, the matter is not really very pressing, but that is the nature of the question; it is always difficult to know where to start.</p></p>

		<p>Debates about the future of the monarchy come in waves. Reforming the 300-year-old Act of Succession, which bars all but Protestants from the throne, is the latest focus of attention. A motion before the House of Commons in the name of the Scottish Nationalists calls for its repeal. As both the heir to the throne and his elder son are members of the Church of England, the matter is not really very pressing, but that is the nature of the question; it is always difficult to know where to start.</p>
<p>When <i>The Independent</i> was launched in 1986, we decided to give brief coverage to royal news. There was lots of other interesting or amusing stuff to cover. Newspapers had become unduly besotted with the Royal Family. And relentless attention imposed a great strain which some individual members evidently found difficult to handle. Who would not? As editor at the time, I had a private bet with myself - that a successful newspaper could manage without royalty.</p><p>As a matter of fact, for good commercial reasons, national newspapers as a whole cannot any longer manage without daily coverage. For the doings of the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh, the Queen's mother, the Queen's sister, Prince Charles and his children, the Princess Royal, the other princes and their families provide the raw material for the most powerful of narrative forms - invented as it was by television, drawing its inspiration from 19th century novels - the soap opera. A large cast is essential. The extended family must contain all ages, from an ancient great grandmother to new baby, and some of them, at least, must behave badly. And if the hangers-on can have among their number former cavalry officers and antique dealers, so much the better. Somebody must play the cad. The British Royal Family and its friends supply every requirement.</p><p>There is real tragedy here. The discovery of the soap opera format unfortunately coincided with two developments. The first was the decision to promote the concept of the wider Royal Family, with a network of royal personages fanning out across the country to carry out their state and charitable duties. No event need be short of a royal presence. And the second was a well-meaning attempt by younger members to get away from the stuffy image of their elders and make themselves more accessible, more natural, more connected to everyday things.</p><p>How sensible and forward looking all this must have seemed, and perhaps still does. But this policy didn't take into account the royal reporters who pry and poke and invent what they cannot discover. The upshot is that the better we have come to know our Royal Family, the more we have transformed them into characters in search of an author. Is this why nearly half the population, according to recent opinion polls, would like the crown to skip a generation and pass to the more or less unknown Prince William rather than to his father, Prince Charles, with whose strengths and weaknesses of character we feel ourselves only too familiar?</p><p>This is the problem. Can the nation at one and the same time view members of the Royal Family as playing parts in a daily serial, as if they were <i>The Archers</i>, and yet revere the most senior of them as head of state? While Queen Elizabeth continues to reign, undoubtedly, yes; but what then? Can the respect we wish to show to a head of state be maintained?</p><p>I am much more bothered by this problem than I am by the constitutional anomalies the monarchy generates. I dislike the monarch's role as Supreme Governor of the Church of England, but it doesn't matter very much. The sovereign's residual powers regarding the calling and dismissal of parliaments and the appointment of the prime minister have not been used in my life time and other arrangements could easily be made. The immense powers of the royal prerogative are in the hands of the prime minister of the day, but these could be dispersed if Parliament so wishes without touching the monarch.</p><p>At this stage in the debate, all one can say is that several things are not going to happen. No pressure will come on the Queen to abdicate; she is hugely respected. That is a brute fact. There is no appetite for a president, however selected. Any name that is suggested, whether former politician or worthy person, is laughed at with bemusement. That is a second brute fact.</p><p>Some deep instinct tells the British people that it is safer to let one well-known family, however dysfunctional it is or may become, provide successive heads of state than any other system experts may dream up. This is not a sentimental view; it is a constitutional preference. Moreover, when the Queen dies, there will be no referendum. There isn't time. "The Queen is dead; long live the King". That is a third brute fact. Let the debate continue. Nothing is going to happen.</p><p>* <i>aws@globalnet.co.uk</i></p>
<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20100709181216/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/andreas-whittam-smith/">More from Andreas Whittam Smith</a></p>
	        <!-- adSurroundStart -->
